AB  - The pharmaceutical industry revolves around the development of molecular formulations to treat/cure diseases. Their main activity is to find and develop molecules that could help cure diseases and disorders. The use of computational approaches, like quantum mechanics (QM), molecular dynamics simulation, mathematical modeling, physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling, process simulation, artificial intelligence (AI), and machine algorithm learning in pharmaceutical research has expanded dramatically in recent decades. The primary principle involved in quantum computing (QC) is quantum physics, which is more efficient, accurate, and faster especially when dealing with large molecules. QC could improve the effectiveness of current CADD (computer-aided drug design) tools that impact the development process including designing proteins. The main purpose of the article is to offer an update on nanoparticulate transdermal drug delivery systems (TDDSs) using quantum computational approaches, which involve the delivery of a drug into or through a skin membrane. Current transdermal drug delivery technologies improve skin permeability for low-dose drugs, which are lipophilic with low molecular weight molecules. Nanoparticles have been discovered to have advantages in medication delivery to target cells or tissues as their structural and chemical compositions play a major role in their transport. Designing the best nanoparticle TDDS is a bit challenging nowadays and leads to an increase in the number of experimental experiments to investigate the properties of the nanoparticle. This chapter discusses the most recent developments in nanoparticles as DDSs. Complementary experimental and computational studies have improved the understanding of nanocarrier mechanism of action and underlying interactions with drugs. The chapter focuses on computer modeling for DDSs. TDDS nanoparticles play an essential role in NDDS for successful therapy with fewer or no side effects than conventional techniques.
