AB  - A new era of technical innovation, by Industry 6.0, is about to take off and is expected to revolutionize industries like catastrophe management. In this chapter, authors have explored on the substantial potential of cutting-edge technologies, such as blockchain, robotics, Internet of Things (IoT), quantum computing, and artificial intelligence (AI) to improve catastrophe resilience, response, and recovery. It analyzes important trends, obstacles, and possibilities for using these technologies in disaster management through a review of the literature as well as industry reports and case studies. With the use of AI and machine learning algorithms, predictive analytics has never been this good, allowing for more precise catastrophe predicting and preemptive responses. With their vast sensor networks, IoT devices offer real-time data collecting and monitoring, which enhances situational awareness and allows for timely notifications. Transparency in transactions and safe data exchange are guaranteed by blockchain technology, which is essential for preserving confidence in disaster relief efforts. Drones and robotics are being used more often in logistics, surveillance, and search and rescue to lower human danger and increase efficiency. With its outstanding processing power, quantum computing manages intricate simulations and data analysis. Industry 6.0 technologies still face obstacles in terms of interoperability, scalability, and reliability when included into disaster management, notwithstanding these developments. Maintaining public trust in data usage and monitoring requires addressing ethical and privacy concerns. Together with providing best practices and creative solutions, this chapter also showcases effective Industry 6.0 technology implementations in current crisis scenarios. It provides suggestions for policymakers, practitioners, and academics on how to best utilize Industry 6.0’s potential by synthesizing these results. In this chapter, authors have discussed about the revolutionary role of the cutting-edge technology in creating disaster management systems that are more adaptable and robust, opening the door to a society that is safer and better equipped to deal with the growing number of natural and man-made risks.
ER  -

